 zero.
 Indeed, every singleton 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\right\} $
\end_inset

 is closed and hence measurable and has measure zero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\right\} =\left[x,x\right].$
\end_inset

 Countable additivity then tells us that every countable set has measure
 zero.
 In particular, the rational numbers have measure zero.
 Do there exist uncountable sets that also have measure zero? We can indeed
 construct such sets.
 Perhaps more surprisingly, we can use a similar construction to show that
 there exist sets of 
\emph on
positive 
\emph default
Lebesgue measure, that nevertheless contain no non-trivial intervals within
 them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:cantorSet"

\end_inset

Let the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_{i}}{3^{i}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is the Cantor set consists of those elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 whose ternary (base 3) representation does not contain any
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in its digits.
 A hurdle with this definition is that the representation is not unique;
 as with any decimal or binary representation, we have things like 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02222222..._{3}=0.1_{3}$
\end_inset

 where the subscripts highlight the fact that we are using ternary representatio
ns.
 A discussion on base-
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 representatiosn of real numbers can be found in Appendix section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:baseBRepresentations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this case, we say that an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is in the Cantor set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 if any one of its representations has coefficients only in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In other words, real numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $0.022222..._{3}\in C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative characterization of the Cantor set is to take the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}:=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and remove the the middle third set 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{1}=\left(\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then from the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}:=\left[0,1\right]\setminus G_{1}=\left[0,\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{2}{3},1\right]$
\end_inset

 remove the middle third of each interval component; that is, remove 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{2}=\left(\frac{1}{9},\frac{2}{9}\right)\cup\left(\frac{7}{9},\frac{8}{9}\right)$
\end_inset

and so on.
 The recursive description of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ G_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}$
\end_inset

 can be given as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G_{1} & =\left(\frac{1}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)\\
G_{n} & =\frac{G_{n-1}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{G_{n-1}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Symmetrically, we recursively define the sets approximating the Cantor set
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ C_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N\cup\left\{ 0\right\} }$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C_{0} & =\left[0,1\right]\\
C_{n} & =\frac{C_{n-1}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{C_{n-1}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:cantorCnDecreasing"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C_{n+1}\subseteq C_{n}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N\cup\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{2}{3},1\right]=C_{1}\subset C_{0}=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{3}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=\frac{x}{3}+\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Next suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n+1}=f\left[C_{n}\right]\cup g\left[C_{n}\right]\subseteq C_{n}.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left[C_{n+1}\right]\subseteq f\left[C_{n}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left[C_{n+1}\right]\subseteq g\left[C_{n}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Together, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n+2}=f\left[C_{n+1}\right]\cup g\left[C_{n+1}\right]\subseteq f\left[C_{n}\right]\cup g\left[C_{n}\right]=C_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorSetIntersectionCn"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C=\bigcap_{n\in\N}C_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will show that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 where write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_{i}}{3^{i}}$
\end_inset

in its base-
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 representation with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

, the following claims are equivalent 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\neq1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We certainly know that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}\neq1$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C_{1}=\left[0,\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{1}{3},1\right].$
\end_inset

 Now assume that that the claims are equivalent for some fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and suppose that for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n+1:a_{i}\neq1.$
\end_inset

 By the induction hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C_{n}$
\end_inset

 and so if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is such that its first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 digits after the delimter are 0 or 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $3x\in C_{n}$
\end_inset

 (again by the hypothesis) and so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\frac{C_{n}}{3}.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}=2$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3\left(x-\frac{2}{3}\right)\in C_{n}$
\end_inset

 by the hypothesis and so 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\frac{C_{n}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\frac{C_{n}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{C_{n}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right)=C_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 which completes one implication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n+1}\subseteq C_{n}$
\end_inset

, our hypothesis tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\neq1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n$
\end_inset

.
 Now 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\frac{C_{n}}{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\frac{C_{n}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n+1}=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3x\notin C_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\left(x-\frac{2}{3}\right)\notin C_{n}$
\end_inset

 and the proof is complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:CantorSetEquiv"

\end_inset

For every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}=\left[0,1\right]\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}G_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 the claim is obvious.
 Suppose the claim holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}=\left[0,1\right]\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C_{n+1} & =\frac{C_{n}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{C_{n}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{3}\left(\left[0,1\right]\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}G_{i}\right)\cup\left(\frac{1}{3}\left(\left[0,1\right]\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}G_{i}\right)+\frac{2}{3}\right)\\
 & =\left(\left[0,\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{2}{3},1\right]\right)\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{G_{i}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{G_{i}}{3}\cup\frac{2}{3}\right)\right)\\
 & =C_{1}\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{G_{i}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{G_{i}}{3}\cup\frac{2}{3}\right)\right)\\
 & =\left[0,1\right]\setminus G_{1}\setminus\bigcup_{i=2}^{n+1}G_{i}\\
 & =\left[0,1\right]\setminus\bigcup_{i=1}^{n+1}G_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorSetClosed"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is closed under the usual topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 is closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}=\frac{C_{n-1}}{3}\cup\left(\frac{C_{n-1}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 is closed if 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{n}$
\end_inset

 is closed for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

 and so the intersection is closed as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorSetMeasureZero"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C\in\borel\left(\R\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\left(C\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is closed its in 
\begin_inset Formula $\borel\left(\R\right).$
\end_inset

 We first prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\left(C_{n}\right)\leq\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 Note that for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 this is obvious, for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(C_{1}\right) & =\lambda\left(\left[0,\frac{1}{3}\right]\cup\left[\frac{2}{3},1\right]\right)\\
 & =\lambda\left(\left[0,\frac{1}{3}\right]\right)+\lambda\left(\left[\frac{2}{3},1\right]\right)\\
 & =\frac{2}{3}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\left(C_{n}\right)\leq\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n}$
\end_inset

 and observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(C_{n+1}\right) & \leq\lambda\left(\frac{C_{n+1}}{3}\right)+\lambda\left(\frac{C_{n}}{3}+\frac{2}{3}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n}+\frac{1}{3}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n}\\
 & =\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n+1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the inequality is by subadditivity, and the first equality by the
 properties (translation invariance and scaling) outlined in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:existenceLebesgueR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Then, by Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:equivalenceContinuityMeasures"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(C\right) & =\lambda\left(\bigcap_{n\in\N}C_{n}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\lambda\left(C_{n}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{n\to\infty}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{n}\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorSetUncountable"

\end_inset

The Cantor set 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is uncountable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Because the Cantor set can be described as the collection of all ternary
 strings with only 0s and 2s, we know by Cantor's diagonal argument that
 such a collection is not countable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorSetDisconnected"

\end_inset

The Cantor set contains no non-trivial (i.e.
