\begin_layout Standard
Another way to establish the uncountability of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is to examine the behavior of the following function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:cantorFunction"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}:\left[0,1\right]\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 be given as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{C}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_{i}}{2^{i}}, & x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{2a_{i}}{3^{i}},a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} \\
\sup_{y\leq x,y\in C}\psi_{C}\left(y\right) & x\in\left[0,1\right]\setminus C
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\emph on
Cantor function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the Cantor function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is well defined since every member of the Cantor set has a 
\emph on
unique 
\emph default
base 3 representation where coefficients are only 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 Here's a practical way to think about the Cantor function.
 First, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is computed from the unique base
\begin_inset Formula $-3$
\end_inset

 representation (i.e.
 the one with only 0s and 2s) by turning all the 2s into 1s and then interpretin
g the resulting string as a binary number.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $x\notin C,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is computed by taking the base-
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, truncating after the first 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and then replacing each 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 before the first 1 with 1s and then interpreting the result as a binary
 number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:imageCantorSetUnderCantorFunctionFull"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left[C\right]=\left[0,1\right].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 has a binary representation 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_{i}}{2^{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We take the terminating expansion to stave off questions about uniqueness
 (i.e.
 the expansion that doesn't end in all 1s).
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{2a_{i}}{3^{i}}
\]

\end_inset

is the unique element in the Cantor set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(x\right)=y$
\end_inset

 which completes the proof.
\end_layout

