\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorFunctionIncreasing"

\end_inset

The Cantor function is non-decreasing i.e for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq y$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{C}\left(x\right)\geq\psi_{C}\left(y\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First suppose both 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq y$
\end_inset

.
 Write the unique expansions 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_{i}}{3^{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{i}}{3^{i}}$
\end_inset

 and notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\geq b_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\N$
\end_inset

 and so clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(x\right)\geq\psi_{C}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The case when both 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\notin C$
\end_inset

 is trivial by the first part and the definition of the supremum.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin C.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq y$
\end_inset

 then then clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(x\right)\geq\psi_{C}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 by the definition and the first part of the proof.
 A similar argument holds if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\geq x$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorFunctionContinuous"

\end_inset

The Cantor function 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is continuous on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is discontinuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is increasing, we have that the limits 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c^{-}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 exist and are in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 since it is closed.
 Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c^{-}\right)<f\left(c^{+}\right)$
\end_inset

 which implies that there is some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c^{-}\right)<y<f\left(c^{+}\right).$
\end_inset

 But then there's no 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)=y$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a non-decreasing and continuous function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, it can be extended to a Stieljes function in an obvious way, define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{\psi_{C}}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1, & x>1\\
\psi_{c}\left(x\right), & x\in\left[0,1\right]\\
0, & x<0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The function 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{\psi_{C}}$
\end_inset

 is still non-decreasing and continuous and so there it induces a Stieljes
 measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\borel\left(\R\right)$
\end_inset

 by Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:stieljesMeasure"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This measure, is in some sense 
\emph on
orthogonal 
\emph default
to the Lebesgue measure, a notion that we will make precise in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:Differentiation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 This idea is intimately connected to the fact that while 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}$
\end_inset

 is differentiable almost everywhere (the meaning of this phrase will be
 made precise later), it is not the integral of its derivative, a fact which
 we shall also establish in that chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cantor function is symmetric, a fact that is important in establishing
 moments of the Cantor distribution in probability theory.
 For now, we use this fact to compute the integral of this function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorFunctionSymmetry"

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(1-x\right)=1-\psi_{C}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

 in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x\in C$
\end_inset

 .
 To see this, write 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{2a_{i}}{3^{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 and then 
\begin_inset Formula $1-x=\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}\frac{\left(2-2a_{i}\right)}{3^{i}}$
\end_inset

