\begin_layout Standard
The Cantor function also has the remarkable property that it is actually
 constant on each interval component of the complement of the Cantor set
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right].$
\end_inset

This is particularly striking since then it's only strictly increasing inside
 the Cantor set, which is a set of measure zero, and yet manages to hit
 every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:cantorFunctionConstantOutside"

\end_inset

The Cantor function is constant on every interval component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]\setminus C.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First note that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}G_{i}=\left[0,1\right]\setminus C$
\end_inset

 is open since each set 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{i}$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Moreover, by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:openSetDisjointUnionInterval"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, there are countably many disjoint open intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ O_{j}\right\} _{j\in\N}\subseteq\left[0,1\right] $
\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigcup_{i=1}^{\infty}G_{i}=\bigcup_{j=1}^{\infty}O_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\bigcup G_{i}$
\end_inset

 and notice that then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in O_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $j.$
\end_inset

 Deffine 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=\sup\left\{ y\in C\mid y\leq x\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

 since the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ y\in\left[0,1\right]\mid y\leq x\right\} $
\end_inset

 are both closed.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in O_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}<z$
\end_inset

 since otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $\min\left\{ z,x\right\} \leq y_{0}\leq\max\left\{ z,x\right\} $
\end_inset

 would mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{j}$
\end_inset

 is not contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]\setminus C$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose that there's some 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in C$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}<y_{1}<z$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}>x$
\end_inset

 (since otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\in\left\{ y\in C\mid y\leq x\right\} $
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}\leq y_{0}$
\end_inset

) which again means that 
\begin_inset Formula $z>y_{1}>x$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{j}\cap C\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 Therefore, it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}=\sup\left\{ y\in C\mid y\leq z\right\} $
\end_inset

 and so for any 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in O_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{C}\left(z\right)=\psi_{C}\left(y_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

, yielding the result.
\end_layout

